Question 5.2.7:

Function: f(x)

Constraint: alpha <= g(x) <= beta

The new method:

  Function: f(x) + sum_1_r [ P(g(x),mu,c)]

  Constraint: x

              where P(g(x),mu,c) = argmin {mu*u+(c/2)*|u|^2}

  Each of these minimizations follows a multiplier method:

    mu^{k+1} = |mu^{k}+c^{k}(g(x)-beta)   mu+c(g(x)-beta)  > 0
               |mu^{k}+c^{k}(g(x)-alpha)  mu+c(g(x)-alpha) < 0
               |0                 otherwise

The new method equivalence to the original function and constraint is through an additional constraint:

  Function: f(x)                         <------->   Function: f(x) + sum_1_r [ P(g(x),mu,c)]

  Constraint: alpha <= g(x)-u <= beta    <------->   Constraint: x

An additional term, u describes the summation found within the right-hand side above. In the Lagrange equation, the term is succinct:

  L(x,lambda,u) = f(x) + lambda*(g(x)-u) <------->   L(x,lambda,u) = f(x) + sum_1_r [ P(g(x),mu,c)] + lambda*x

Where lambda*u equals sum_1_r [ P(g(x),mu,c)] in the right-side Lagrangian.

Multiplier methods show similar relationships by lambda^{r+1} = lambda^{r} + (c/2)*h(x)^2.

      lambda*u = lambda^{r+1}*u

               = (lambda^{r} + (c/2)*|u|) * u

               = lambda^{r}*u + (c/2)*|u|^2

               = argmin { mu^{r}*u+(c^{r}/2)*|u|^2 }

               = sum_1_r [ P(g(x),mu,c)]




